    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When describing chaotic or overly complicated behavior, you need professional language that translates \"troublesome\" into observable, measurable workplace behaviors. Avoid subjective words like \"chaotic\" or \"erratic\" because those are too vague and sound like a personal attack. Instead, focus on the *output* of that behavior.\n\nYou could describe it as a tendency toward \"overcomplication in problem-solving\" or a \"preference for high-intensity debate over consensus-building.\" If their energy is disruptive, frame it as a need to \"channel enthusiasm into structured contribution.\"\n\nFor instance, instead of saying they are troublesome, you might state: \"We encourage [Employee Name] to focus on streamlining complex issues. There have been instances where the pursuit of exhaustive detail has extended discussion timelines unnecessarily, suggesting an opportunity to prioritize efficiency alongside thoroughness.\" This addresses the *result* (wasted time/complexity) without labeling their internal state.\n\nThis approach is much safer because you are critiquing the *method* of their contribution, not their inherent nature. It gives them a tangible skill to work on—prioritization or conciseness—which is much easier to address than their \"vibe.\"\n\nIt's a delicate tightrope",
      "source": "target",
